{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-topic-topic-tsx","path":"/topics/gilberts-syndrome/","result":{"data":{"firstChapter":{"id":"61548d32-4743-5f65-9106-1d1b2c8a5b41","slug":"summary","fullItemName":"Summary","subChapters":[],"depth":1,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 988ee692-2575-453e-8272-ede1ab095699 --><h1>Gilbert's syndrome: Summary</h1><!-- end field 988ee692-2575-453e-8272-ede1ab095699 -->","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item a06aeca9-f871-4469-9411-9c0b8da1ef50 --><!-- begin field 98d30418-ba93-465f-88a6-49965f55fb7a --><ul><li>Gilbert's syndrome is an inherited (usually autosomal recessive) metabolic disorder that causes intermittent, isolated raised unconjugated bilirubin levels, due to defective conjugating enzymes in the liver. There is otherwise normal liver function, and no evidence of haemolysis.</li><li>Gilbert's syndrome is a common cause of isolated unconjugated hyperbilirubinemia.<ul><li>In western Europe, 5–10% of the population are affected, but many cases remain undiagnosed. At least 30% of people with Gilbert's syndrome never develop symptoms.</li></ul></li><li>Examination may reveal mild jaundice and signs of a precipitating illness, such as infection, but no hepatosplenomegaly or signs of chronic liver disease.</li><li>Gilbert's syndrome can be diagnosed when a person has:<ul><li>Unconjugated hyperbilirubinemia (often noted on several occasions).</li><li>No evidence of haemolysis (normal full blood count, reticulocyte count, and blood film).</li><li>Normal liver enzyme levels.</li><li>No evidence of liver disease.</li></ul></li><li>Other causes of unconjugated hyperbilirubinemia include haemolysis, genetic causes such as Crigler-Najjar syndrome, drugs (methyldopa and sulfasalazine can cause haemolysis; rifampicin can impair hepatic bilirubin clearance), and physiological neonatal jaundice.</li><li>No treatment is required for Gilbert’s syndrome.</li><li>Gilbert's syndrome does not cause chronic liver disease.</li><li>Jaundice in Gilbert's syndrome may be provoked by dieting or fasting, surgery, dehydration, alcohol ingestion, infectious illness, heavy physical exertion, and lack of sleep.<ul><li>Any associated episode of jaundice is self-limiting, is not a sign of serious illness, and is not infectious.</li><li>Gemfibrozil (a fibrate) when used alone or in combination with statins should be used with caution in people with Gilbert's syndrome, as there is an increased risk of drug toxicity.</li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field 98d30418-ba93-465f-88a6-49965f55fb7a --><!-- end item a06aeca9-f871-4469-9411-9c0b8da1ef50 -->","topic":{"id":"9bb2b66b-9dcb-5ca7-ac32-56b20abf186b","topicId":"377bda8d-d3d4-4db0-9e52-f37661e8dd80","topicName":"Gilbert's syndrome","slug":"gilberts-syndrome","aliases":[],"chapters":[{"id":"61548d32-4743-5f65-9106-1d1b2c8a5b41","slug":"summary","fullItemName":"Summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"8713d500-1912-5e94-9e2a-41cc82c4f2ec","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","subChapters":[]},{"id":"6ad04134-a509-5de0-893f-ae8194a670e7","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","subChapters":[{"id":"e49b7532-5573-5509-8cc6-aaac9da62112","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"988f1432-4338-5cac-ab53-356beb3f6ffa","slug":"update","fullItemName":"Update"}]},{"id":"11acffce-feeb-5a59-a9ee-5e20368b33be","slug":"goals-outcome-measures","fullItemName":"Goals and outcome measures","subChapters":[{"id":"72e476f3-3c50-591b-8b11-a18202a33e02","slug":"goals","fullItemName":"Goals"},{"id":"e206d7f3-d3f0-5956-b981-500f313f92e2","slug":"outcome-measures","fullItemName":"Outcome measures"},{"id":"81c9afa4-2c89-5fdf-9c64-d31f2ecd1f4c","slug":"audit-criteria","fullItemName":"Audit criteria"},{"id":"eeb0d33d-78c1-53ca-afd5-2904551c6a18","slug":"qof-indicators","fullItemName":"QOF indicators"},{"id":"a21c1e57-9202-5a0a-be2e-5a142c8f900d","slug":"qipp-options-for-local-implementation","fullItemName":"QIPP